\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces patX methodology overview: The process begins with time series or spatial data, then applies multiple signal transformations to create parallel views of the data. Iterative pattern discovery then: (1) proposes candidate pattern parameters (channel, transform, control points, position range, width), (2) generates a spline pattern, (3) computes min-window MSE dissimilarity features between pattern and transformed signal segments, and (4) evaluates model performance via cross-validation. The best pattern is appended to the feature set and the procedure repeats until adding a new pattern no longer improves performance.}}{8}{figure.caption.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:patx_methodology}{{1}{8}{patX methodology overview: The process begins with time series or spatial data, then applies multiple signal transformations to create parallel views of the data. Iterative pattern discovery then: (1) proposes candidate pattern parameters (channel, transform, control points, position range, width), (2) generates a spline pattern, (3) computes min-window MSE dissimilarity features between pattern and transformed signal segments, and (4) evaluates model performance via cross-validation. The best pattern is appended to the feature set and the procedure repeats until adding a new pattern no longer improves performance}{figure.caption.2}{}}
